WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:03:40.400 --> 00:03:43.284
Professor Paul Bloom:
I'd like to welcome people to

00:03:43.284 --> 00:03:45.410
this course, Introduction to
Psychology.

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:48.729
My name is Dr. Paul Bloom.
I'm professor of this course.

00:03:48.729 --> 00:03:54.896
And what this is going to be is
a comprehensive introduction to

00:03:54.896 --> 00:03:59.833
the study of the human mind.
So, we are going to cover a

00:03:59.833 --> 00:04:03.449
very, very wide range of topics
including brains,

00:04:03.449 --> 00:04:05.645
children, language,
sex, memory,

00:04:05.645 --> 00:04:07.983
madness, disgust,
racism and love,

00:04:07.983 --> 00:04:10.862
and many others.
We're going to talk about

00:04:10.862 --> 00:04:13.727
things like the proper
explanation for differences

00:04:13.727 --> 00:04:17.663
between men and women;
the question of whether animals

00:04:17.663 --> 00:04:21.179
can learn language;
the puzzle of what grosses us

00:04:21.179 --> 00:04:23.556
out;
the problem of why some of us

00:04:23.556 --> 00:04:26.589
eat too much and what we could
do to stop;

00:04:26.589 --> 00:04:30.000
the question of why people go
crazy in groups;

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.269
research into whether you could
trust your childhood memories;

00:04:34.269 --> 00:04:38.930
research into why some of us
get depressed and others don't.

00:04:38.930 --> 00:04:43.943
The style of this is there'll
be two lectures a week,

00:04:43.943 --> 00:04:48.877
as well as course readings.
Now, to do well in the course,

00:04:48.877 --> 00:04:53.010
you have to attend both the
lectures and do the readings.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:55.468
There will be some overlap.
In some cases,

00:04:55.468 --> 00:04:57.940
the lectures will be quite
linked to the readings.

00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:00.844
But there will be some parts of
the readings that will not find

00:05:00.844 --> 00:05:04.198
their way into the lectures,
and some lectures--some entire

00:05:04.198 --> 00:05:07.769
lectures that will not connect
at all to the readings.

00:05:07.769 --> 00:05:12.439
So, to pursue this course
properly you have to do both.

00:05:12.439 --> 00:05:15.837
What this means is that if you
miss a class you need to get

00:05:15.837 --> 00:05:19.234
notes, and so you should get
them from a friend or from the

00:05:19.234 --> 00:05:23.523
person sitting next to you.
The slides are going to be made

00:05:23.523 --> 00:05:26.416
available online.
So, one of the things you don't

00:05:26.416 --> 00:05:28.720
have to do is you don't have to
write this down.

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:31.711
You take notes any way you
choose, but if you don't get

00:05:31.711 --> 00:05:34.259
anything on there it'll be
available online.

00:05:34.259 --> 00:05:37.215
I'm going to post it in a
format which will be black and

00:05:37.215 --> 00:05:40.386
white and easy to print out so
you don't have to worry about

00:05:40.386 --> 00:05:43.281
this.
But again, attending to the

00:05:43.281 --> 00:05:47.569
slides is not a substitute for
attending class.

00:05:47.569 --> 00:05:51.173
There's a textbook,
Peter Gray's Psychology,

00:05:51.173 --> 00:05:55.930
5th edition, and there's also a
collection of short readings,

00:05:55.930 --> 00:05:59.050
The Norton Reader edited by
Gary Marcus.

00:05:59.050 --> 00:06:01.925
It's an excellent textbook;
it's an excellent collection,

00:06:01.925 --> 00:06:05.786
and you should get them both.
They're available at Labyrinth

00:06:05.786 --> 00:06:09.209
bookstore on York Street or you
get them online.

00:06:09.209 --> 00:06:12.303
I should note that last time I
taught the course I used the

00:06:12.303 --> 00:06:15.318
Marcus Reader,
and when Professor Marvin Chun

00:06:15.318 --> 00:06:18.777
taught his course last semester
he used Peter Gray's 5^(th)

00:06:18.777 --> 00:06:21.319
edition textbook.
So, there may be a lot of used

00:06:21.319 --> 00:06:24.806
copies floating around.
You should feel free to try to

00:06:24.806 --> 00:06:28.279
get one of those.
The evaluation goes like this.

00:06:28.279 --> 00:06:30.769
There is a Midterm and there is
a Final.

00:06:30.769 --> 00:06:33.491
The Final will not be held in
